;D   Sep 4, 2019 Chapter 634: Maya the Bee Maya the Bee (German: Die Biene Maja) was the main character of a German book, Zeichentrick (cartoon), as well as later comic book series and animated television series, first written by Waldemar Bonsels and published in 1912. 
The book would be published in many other languages and was used by the Nazis as well as the later National Monarchists and Fascist Royalist to indoctrinate children. 
The stories revolve around a little bee named Maya and her friends Willy the bee, Flip the grasshopper (referred to as "Willi, short for Wilhelm and "Philip" respectively in some versions), Mrs. 
Cassandra (Maya's teacher), and many other insects and other creatures. 
The book depicts Maya's development from an adventurous youngster to a responsible adult member of bee society. 
While the Nazis used the books and their own turn on them to indoctrinate children to obey a authoritarian rule and do everything for their overall society, the National Monarchists and Fascist Royalist in the German Empire and later the Rest of the Axis Central Powers took it even one step further. 
They used the book and other media around Maya for the mass indoctrination of the youth, boys, girls and even young teenagers alike. 
In their version they focused on how Maya served and protected her aristocratic Bee hive and her monarchy the Queen Bee at all coasts. 
The stories of Maya therefore became a tool of Axis Central Power, National Monarchists and Fascist Royalist propaganda teaching even the young that monarchism, royalist and aristocracy were the most natural and logical order on the world, both in nature and in the eyes of the godly creator. 
They tough them that all solitary animals had evolved into some form of hierarchic society and order, yes that those most evolved created outright royal states like insects did (that even knew agriculture, livestock farming and even forms of forced-labor and slavery) and that doing so was a sign of higher evolution and society in their argumentation and teachings. 
The propaganda and influence that the German Empire and later other Axis Central Powers and even National Monarchists and Fascist Royalist outside of their faction used Maya and her friends and adventures for their own ideological and propagandist goals, including the Japanese and their Co-Prosperity Sphere later on, were Giga and Eiga of Maya were produced by themselves, like みつばちマーヤの冒険, Mitsubachi Māya no Bōken (The Adventures of Maya the Bee), with more Asian looking and Asian named animals compared to other versions of Maya and her friends. 
For this reasons Maya the Bee never became quit popular in democratic or anti-authoritarian, anti-aristrocratic states and societies after the Second Great War outside of the Axis Central Powers, the Co-Prosperity Sphere and other National Monarchists, Fascist Royalist and Coprospist regions.   
